<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli Prime Minister Wraps Up Visit to Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli Prime Minister Wraps Up Visit to Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Grachev, Rabin Discuss Military Cooperation </H4>

<F P=102> MK2704095094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 27 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK2704095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Pavel Felgengauer report in the "Generals" column: "The </F>
Two Countries' Armies Warily Are Getting Ready to Cooperate" 
under general headline: "Israel Asks Russia To Influence the 
Arabs"] 
  [Text] Yesterday for the first time in history Russian 
Defense Minister Pavel Grachev held negotiations with Israeli 
Defense Minister Yitzhaq Rabin. The meeting lasted longer than 
planned, and General Rabin was therefore somewhat late at the 
General Staff Academy, where he gave a lecture on the Israeli 
"science of victory." 
  The Israeli Army has long been a subject of interest to some 
Russian military leaders as a possible model for organizing 
future Russian armed forces. Especially the process of raising 
extremely combat-efficient troops with conscripts and 
reservists, the organization of a really universal military 
conscription system, and other features that set the Israeli 
Army apart from the U.S. Army, which for several years has been 
proffered to our military as the key model to emulate. 
  But even more than military cooperation with the Israeli 
Army, Russia is interested in the Arab arms market. Gen. 
Grachev admitted the similarity of the two countries' military 
doctrines and accepted in principle an invitation to go to 
Israel on an official visit, although its date has not been 
fixed: "The question will be considered at expert level." 
Since last summer an Israeli military attache -- Colonel 
Mikha'el Shtiglits (before 1972, a USSR citizen) -- has been 
working in Moscow. At the same time the Russian Federation 
Defense Ministry is only planning to open its attache office in 
Tel Aviv. Gen. Grachev announced that "only after the attaches 
have elaborated on the problem will it be possible to talk about 
the prospects for military cooperation." 
  As a result, these talks between Generals Rabin and Grachev 
were devoted mainly to discussing the general political 
situation in the Middle East. A high-ranking participant in the 
negotiations on the Russian side told me that "matters of 
military and technical cooperation have not been discussed." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

