<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli Prime Minister Wraps Up Visit to Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli Prime Minister Wraps Up Visit to Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Grachev To Visit Israel </H4>

<F P=102> LD2604154194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1433 
GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2604154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Yuriy Tyssovskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 26 Apr -- The considerable similarity of 
Russian and Israeli military doctrines was stressed today by 
Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev after holding talks with 
Yitzhaq Rabin, Israeli prime minister and defense minister. The 
meeting lasted more than an hour. 
  During the meeting the head of the Israeli Government, who 
was a combat general in the recent past, set out the main 
principles of Israel's military doctrine. Theoretically 
Israel's defensive strategy corresponds to a considerable degree 
with our own doctrine -- both of them are based on defense, the 
Russian minister pointed out. The only difference is that we 
mould our defenses in different ways. Their effectiveness 
depends on equipment which both armies use. 
  Pavel Grachev stressed that the Russian leadership attaches 
special importance to the achievement of peace in the Near East 
since this region is in direct proximity to Russia's borders. 
Failure to settle Near East problems could have unpredictable 
consequences, including ethnic and religious ones, for the 
entire world, including Russia. In this connection it is 
essential to make every effort to bring about a political 
settlement of the Arab-Israeli conflict. This can only be 
achieved through joint efforts. 
  Pavel Grachev noted the importance of varied, including 
military, cooperation between Russia and Israel. Naturally, he 
said, from the results of the first meeting we cannot examine 
the possibilities opening up before us in detail. But a 
mechanism for implementing these plans already exists: a 
military attache from Israel is already working in Moscow, at 
the end of April or beginning of May the apparatus of a Russian 
military attache will be working in Israel. We shall charge 
them with working out the relevant program, Grachev said. Today 
our guest in his capacity as minister of defense has invited me 
to make an official visit to Israel, and there we shall outline 
a plan for our future bilateral relations in the military field. 
  Israel's prime minister stated that the Russian leadership, 
and first and foremost Russian President Boris Yeltsin, had 
assured him that Russia is striving to achieve the establishment 
of peace in the Near East. This striving, Y. Rabin said, we 
also share, although we have different contacts and relations 
with the third parties. When the aims are identical, however, 
corresponding interests also emerge that will, I hope, lead to 
the successful completion of the Arab-Israeli talks. 
  After the meeting Yitzhaq Rabin delivered a lecture to an 
audience at the Academy of the General Staff on the subject of 
military doctrine in Israel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

