<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli Prime Minister Wraps Up Visit to Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli Prime Minister Wraps Up Visit to Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Rabin Views Relations With Russia </H4>

<F P=102> LD2704185694 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1700 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2704185694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] In an exclusive interview to Ostankino, [Israeli 
Prime Minister] Yitzhaq Rabin expressed his satisfaction that 
the main purpose of Russian policy in the Middle East is to 
ensure peace, security, and stability. The Israeli prime 
minister believes that by making its actions in the 
international arena more active last month, our country is 
entering a new period of foreign and domestic policy. As far as 
the Middle East settlement is concerned, Yitzhaq Rabin highly 
estimated the role of Russia and the United States as mediators 
in the progress of the Israeli-Palestinian dialogue. However, 
he believes the solution of the problem depends, above all, on 
the sides involved in the conflict. The prime minister 
expressed Israel's interest in extending bilateral contacts with 
Russia and said in future they will spread to the military 
sphere. Yitzhaq Rabin believes the forthcoming visit by Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev to Tel Aviv will be the first step in the 
development of Israeli-Russian cooperation in this field. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

