<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli Prime Minister Wraps Up Visit to Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli Prime Minister Wraps Up Visit to Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Holds News Conference </H4>

<F P=102> LD2704202794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2023 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2704202794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Svetlana Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] St. Petersburg April 27 TASS -- Israeli Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin gave a short news conference at the end 
of his one-day visit to St. Petersburg on Wednesday. 
  Before leaving by plane for Tel-Aviv, Rabin expressed hope 
that fulfilment of the bilateral agreements signed earlier in 
Moscow will contribute to developing cooperation between the two 
countries. 
  The Israeli prime minister met with deputy head of St. 
Petersburg administration Aleksey Kudrin. The exchange of ideas 
proved useful for the Russian party, because Israel earlier used 
to tackle the problems which Russia faces now. These include 
controlling the inflation, privatization (especially, 
privatization of housing construction) and developing the 
agro-industrial complex. 
  Asked to comment on his decision to fly aboard an ordinary 
Israeli plane together with 170 emigrants from Kiev and 25 from 
St. Petersburg, rather than aboard a chartered one, like he did 
when he arrived in Russia, Rabin said he wanted to share -- if 
only for once -- the sentiments of those who had made the hard 
choice to leave their birth-places for ever. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

