<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Lauds South African Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Lauds South African Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604195494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1909 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2604195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia is firmly convinced that supporters of terror 
in South Africa will not manage to impede the advent of a new 
society, that South Africans will make their choice in favor of 
democracy and peace in the country, a spokesman for the Russian 
Foreign Ministry, Grigory Karasin, told a briefing in Moscow 
Tuesday. 
  Karasin pointed out that for the first time in South 
Africa's 
history its people cast their ballots for a non-racial 
parliament. 
  According to Karasin, Russia, which made a considerable 
contribution to dismantling the apartheid regime, believes in a 
new South Africa's future. U.N.-sponsored Russian observers in 
South Africa and a number of official observers from Russia are 
another sign of this, the diplomat said. 
  At the same time, Karasin pointed out that in South Africa 
there remained forces which did not hope to win electors' 
sympathy in a fair struggle under equal conditions and vainly 
tried to stop the historical process and torpedo the elections. 
"This is how the explosion of a car in Johannesburg near the 
building where the ANC headquarters and affiliates of a number 
of other political parties are situated should be understood," 
Karasin pointed out. 

</TEXT>

