<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Allowance of IAEA Inspection Praised </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Allowance of IAEA Inspection Praised </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2804055994 Moscow Radio Moscow in Korean 1200 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2804055994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the Today's World" program] </F>
  [Summary from poor reception] The DPRK has decided to 
allow the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] to inspect 
nuclear facilities in Yongbyon near Pyongyang. This has evoked 
a positive reaction among countries concerned. Pyongyang had 
not permitted the agency's special inspection of DPRK nuclear 
facilities in Yongbyon, and are thus suspected of developing 
nuclear weapons. 
  As the dispute over the nuclear issue of the peninsula 
further deteriorated, the position of some neighboring countries 
became more hardline. First of all, Pyongyang, Seoul, and 
Washington respectively assumed hardline positions. Pyongyang 
complained about the IAEA's unfair attitude in dealing with the 
North Korean nuclear issue. This made the IAEA's inspection 
more difficult. 
  On the other hand, the United States and the ROK were 
attempting to apply pressure on Pyongyang by talking about 
imposing economic saanctions or resuming the Team Spirity joint 
military exercise. 
  U.S. Secretary of State Cristopher said that the change in 
Pyongyang's position toward the IAEA's inspections is a good, 
positive phenomenon. 
  Son Song-pil, DPRK ambassador to Russia, said that the IAEA 
inspection team scheduled to arrive in Yongbyon will be provided 
with all the conditions necessary for its work. 
  We can say that such a position of Pyongyang totally 
corresponds not only with the interests of the DPRK itself but 
also with the interests of other countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

