<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Views Visit, Nuclear Weapons </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Peng Views Visit, Nuclear Weapons </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2704153494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1504 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2704153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by KAZTAG correspondent Ivan Zakharchenko for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Alma-Ata [Almaty] 27 April TASS -- Premier of the 
Chinese State Council Li peng said at a news conference in 
Alma-Ata devoted to the results of his visit to Turkmenistan, 
Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan and Kazakhstan that his talks with 
leaders of these countries were successful and contributed to 
further strengthening of friendship, mutual understanding and 
the expansion of economic, political and cultural ties. 
  The Chinese premier pointed out that China accounts for the 
smallest number of weapons of mass destruction possessed by 
nuclear states. The existence of such weapons has a purely 
defensive character and China pledged not to be the first to use 
such weapons, the Chinese premier said, reminding of basic 
principles of the Chinese military and political doctrine. 
  The Chinese premier pointed out, in particular, that a 
document on the inviolability of existing frontiers was signed 
between China and Kazakhstan for the first time. China expects 
to sign a similar document soon with Kyrgyzstan, Li Peng said. 
  Touching upon Russo-Chinese relations, Li Peng described 
them 
as "useful and fruitful." 
  Late on Wednesday the Chinese premier had a one-to-one 
meeting with Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev. 
  On Thursday morning the Chinese premier and his entourage 
will leave Alma-Ata. 

</TEXT>

