<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimea Leaders Urge Resumption of Fleet Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimea Leaders Urge Resumption of Fleet Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604112994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1104 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2604112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vadim Byrkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow 26 April TASS -- President Yuriy Meshkov of 
the Republic of the Crimea, Admiral Eduard Baltin, commander of 
the Black Sea Fleet, and Viktor Semyonov, chairman of the 
Sevastopol City Council of People's Deputies have issued a joint 
statement urging the presidents of Russia and Ukraine to resume 
the interrupted Russo-Ukrainian talks on the Black Sea Fleet and 
"to act as the guarantors of peace in the Republic of the 
Crimea," a spokesman at the fleet press centre told ITAR-TASS by 
telephone. 
  The authors of the statement expressed utter regret and 
concern over the frustration of the Russo-Ukrainian talks on 
dividing the fleet. They believe that the "struggle for 
political power and the presidency of Ukraine becomes a factor 
which can turn the process of negotiations on the problems of 
the Black Sea Fleet into a military conflict." 
  Attempts are being made to lay the blame for a possible 
break-up of Ukraine's statehood on the Republic of the Crimea 
and severely punish it for that. It is no problem by means of 
provocations to bring about an unstable situation in the 
republic and, making use of that, introduce a state-of-emergency 
regime, putting Russia-Ukraine relations on the brink of war, 
the authors of the statement maintain. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

