<H3> <TI>   Kurds Crossing Illegally From Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kurds Crossing Illegally From Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2804131894 Tallinn BNS in English 1013 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2804131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Apr 28, BNS -- Estonian border authorities 
have provided to Russia materials to prove that the group of 
Kurds which arrived in Estonia on April 6 had come from Russia. 
The Russian side didn't accept the proof, claiming it was 
impossible to cross the border illegally from their side, since 
they are guarding the border 24 hours a day. 
  Three students from Afghanistan, currently studying in 
Moscow, on Wednesday [27 April] applied for an Estonian visa at 
the country's embassy in the Russian capital. The students said 
their parents were among the group of Kurds who came to Estonia 
illegally. 
  Estonia refused to issue visas to the Afghan students, 
saying 
it still insists that Russia would take back the Kurds who 
crossed the border illegally. 

</TEXT>

