<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Budget Committee Suggests Reducing Foreign Loans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Budget Committee Suggests Reducing Foreign Loans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804163594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1607 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2804163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The State Duma Committee on Budget, Taxes and 
Finances considers it necessary to limit Russia's foreign loans 
in 1994 to 4.7 billion dollars instead of 5.7 billion dollars 
proposed by the government. 
  The committee prepared a corresponding draft law and a 
report 
on the need to reduce foreign loans. 
  This year the Russian government intends to repay 4.7 
billion 
dollars of foreign debts. The State Duma Committee believes 
that the reduction of loans by the same amount would make the 
size of attracted credits dependent upon the ability of Russia's 
economy to service the foreign debt. 
  Russia's foreign debt without taking into account the debt 
to 
East European countries and delayed commercial payments exceeded 
80 billion dollars by the beginning of 1994. Annual payments 
which Russia is to make according to the schedule of servicing 
and repayments of the principal amount of the debt exceeded 20 
billion dollars in 1992-1993. Holding talks with the clubs of 
Russia's creditors allowed it to reduce repayments of the 
foreign debt to 2 billion dollars in 1992 and 2.2 billion 
dollars in 1993. The servicing and repayment of the foreign 
debt in 1994, taking into account the amount delayed from last 
year, demands the granting of 32 billion dollars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

