<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Arrives in Orenburg, Gives Interview </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Arrives in Orenburg, Gives Interview </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904104194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0950 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Nikolay Goncharov] </F>
  [Text] Orenburg April 29 TASS -- Russian Premier Viktor 
Chernomyrdin who arrived in Orenburg on Friday to celebrate the 
250th jubilee of the Orenburg region (gubernia in the past), 
said at the airport to journalists that the government will make 
payments, first of all, to peasants after the federal budget is 
approved by parliament. 
  "Concerns, now experienced by all Russia, are characteristic 
of the Orenburg region too," he stressed. "Let us try and 
settle at least some of them," he added. 
  Journalists welcoming Chernomyrdin at the airport also asked 
him other questions. They were interested when a package of 
documents on press support is put into operation and what its 
essence is. 
  The premier replied that the government is also interested 
in 
this question. He expressed doubt that Russian people need the 
press and television in such amounts as now. "The state will 
maintain several newspapers and tv channels," the cabinet head 
assured. 
  "However, this is for the time being. Experience will show 
what to do in future. I'm against commanding the media. The 
government plans to issue a special decision on questions of the 
press, which do not brook any delay. The decision will be 
issued before the adoption of a press law which will be soon 
approved." 
  Asked by ITAR-TASS about his attitude to the Russian 
president's decision to suspend till July the execution of the 
cabinet's decision on raising customs duties on imports, 
Chernomyrdin noted: "We postponed this decision ourselves, since 
we `outdid' ourselves." 
  "There are international norms: When changes are made in 
customs duties, three months are given to conclude new contracts 
and to establish contacts. We should also abide by this 
three-month norm by some items." 
  The premier's trip to the Orenburg region will last three 
days. 

</TEXT>

