<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Shokhin Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Shokhin Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904065394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0100 
GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2904065394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Mineyev] </F>
  [Excerpts] Brussels, 29 Apr -- Russia and the European 
Union are completing their consultations on the partnership and 
cooperation agreement, Russian Deputy Prime Minister Aleksandr 
Shokhin told an ITAR-TASS correspondent during his brief 
stopover in Brussels on his way from the United States to Moscow. 
  A number of barriers blocking the progress toward agreement 
have been removed, said the deputy head of the Russian 
Government. He added however that a meeting between him and 
Leon Brittan, deputy chairman of the European Commission, would 
be necessary to reach a final agreement on questions of 
principle. Among other things, they will discuss trade in 
enriched uranium. Russia has proposed compromise solutions, 
which will have to be developed into approved texts. If this is 
achieved, then the agreement could be initialled while Greece is 
still chairing the EC -- that is, before the end of June -- and 
it could be signed when Germany takes over the chairmanship. 
  Aleksandr Shokhin, the official head of the Russian 
delegation at the talks in Brussels, was delayed in the United 
States by the funeral of Richard Nixon, so that his stay in the 
"capital of Europe" has been curtailed to just one night. His 
meeting with Leon Brittan will take place in Moscow where the 
latter is going on 1 May. [passage omitted] 
  As it deals with global issues, Russia is striving to build 
relations on a partnership basis; it does not merely ask for 
help but insists that there should be universal rules, 
beneficial both to her and to other countries, said Deputy Prime 
Minister A. Shokhin. "This will be the leitmotiv in our contacts 
both with the G-7 and with international financial organizations 
-- not aid in exchange for reforms but creating general 
mechanisms of interaction between partners," Aleksandr Shokhin 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

