<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Syrian Military Deal Covers Only Defensive Systems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Syrian Military Deal Covers Only Defensive Systems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2804163594 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 29 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2804163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aleksandr Sychev: "Moscow Considering Writing </F>
Off Syrian Debts"] 
  [Text] "The Syrians have acknowledged their debt to Russia 
and our political succession. That is major progress. The 
talks will continue," according to Viktor Posuvalyuk, the 
Russian president's special representative in the Near East and 
member of the government delegation which has been conducting 
talks in Damascus under the leadership of Oleg Soskovets, first 
deputy chairman of the Russian Federation Government. The 
delegation members prefer not to go into the details of the 
continuing talks, but the idea of writing off part of the Syrian 
debt was apparently discussed in Damascus. 
  The problem of the debt, which stands at approximately $10 
billion, is the most acute one in our relations with Syria. A 
large part of the debt results from major purchases of Soviet 
weapons in the seventies and eighties. 
  Skokov's [as published] trip to Syria was supposed not only 
to revive the frozen relations with a partner in the Near East 
who was once important to the USSR. The visit was part of the 
revitalized Russian policy in the region, which Moscow sees as 
the second most important area after Yugoslavia in which it can 
demonstrate Russia's new role in world affairs as a great power. 
  Russia is pretty well placed in the region. It has the 
opportunity to establish qualitatively new links with old 
friends. It has many former compatriots in Israel. The first 
test was the request made by the Russian delegation in Damascus 
to help find Israeli servicemen missing during the Israeli 
invasion of Lebanon in 1982. Moscow could also be of use in the 
process of the settlement of the Syrian-Israeli conflict over 
the Golan Heights. captured by Israel in 1967. U.S. Secretary 
of State Warren Christopher intends to pass to Damascus a 
proposal on the stage-by-stage return of the occupied 
territories over a period of 10 years. 
  Russia's growing importance in Near East affairs was 
acknowledged in Moscow by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin. 
Evidently, it was this that prompted him to settle for Moscow's 
promise not to sell new offensive weapons to Syria, a matter 
that was broached in connection with the agreement on 
military-technical cooperation signed by Soskovets in Damascus. 
Moscow will resume supplies of spare parts and also purely 
defensive weapon systems. It is to be hoped that this treaty 
will not lead to a further increase in Syria's debt to Russia, 
which is facing massive financial problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

