<H3> <TI>   Irish Foreign Minister Outlines Talks Agenda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Irish Foreign Minister Outlines Talks Agenda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804220694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1616 
GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2804220694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Sergey Oleynik] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 28 Apr -- "I would describe the current 
state of Russian-Irish relations as excellent," said Irish 
Deputy Prime Minister of Foreign Affairs Dick Spring, in an 
interview with an ITAR-TASS correspondent. Spring is in Moscow 
on an official visit. 
  "I expect to see progress in two directions as a result of 
the present visit: on the political front and in the economy," 
Spring stressed. "For the first, a broad range of international 
problems -- among them, reform of the UN, disarmament, 
nonproliferation of nuclear weapons, and the latest events in 
Russia and the region -- are to be discussed at tomorrow's 
meeting with Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev. On many 
of these issues, our positions are very close and we hope to 
strengthen the mutual understanding we have achieved and to map 
out prospects for future work." 
  One important practical result of the visit should be the 
conclusion of a bilateral agreement on avoiding double taxation. 
"Today, I had meetings with representatives of Irish business 
circles in Moscow," Spring said, "and all of them drew my 
attention to the importance of adopting a document of this kind. 
  "Generally speaking, we are very proud of the successes of 
Irish business in your country," Spring emphasized, "and are 
doing everything we can through diplomatic channels to assist 
it." Muscovites are well aware of Irish company Aer Rianta's 
joint ventures -- the Irish House on Arbat Street and the Duty 
Free shops at Sheremetyevo II and in a number of the capital's 
hotels. Other Irish companies are following Aer Rianta's lead. 
I note the expansion of the Garden Ring supermarket chain in 
Moscow. 
  Ireland is also involved in projects to develop Russian 
management and rebuild the food sector, the municipal economy, 
and the services sector, including those being implemented 
within the European Union's programs. "But the main thing is 
that Irish businessmen are optimistic and are ready to expand 
their activities in Russia. I share their optimism," the deputy 
prime minister concluded. 

</TEXT>

