Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   All Nuclear Weaponry in Kazakhstan Belongs to Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    All Nuclear Weaponry in Kazakhstan Belongs to Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804185494 Moscow NTV in Russian 1800 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2804185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Some very interesting facts were made public today 
in Moscow's Artillery and Missile Forces Academy. A film crew 
from the Segodnya program were the only journalists present. 
  [Correspondent Ivliyev] The nuclear strategic missiles based 
in Kazakhstan belong to Russia -- this is the sensational news 
reported today by the Colonel General Igor Sergeyev, commander 
in chief of strategic missile forces, at a briefing for foreign 
military attaches, which took place in the Dzerzhinskiy Military 
Academy. 
  [Begin Sergeyev recording] A month ago, on 28 March, an 
agreement was reached during the Russian-Kazakhstan talks on 
giving Russian status to the formations and units of strategic 
missile forces stationed temporarily on Kazakhstan territory. A 
timescale was also agreed for the withdrawal of nuclear warheads 
to Russian territory. [end recording] 
  [Ivliyev] The agreement reached means that the personnel of 
the missile forces receive Russian citizenship. After the stage 
by stage withdrawal of missile force units from Kazakhstan is 
completed, the launch shafts will be dismantled, apparently by 
Russian specialists. Thus, all three CIS states -- Ukraine, 
Belarus, and Kazakhstan -- on whose territory nuclear weaponry 
remained after the collapse of the USSR, now have a treaty with 
Russia on its removal. In a few years, if these countries 
fulfill their obligations, Igor Sergeyev stressed, they will 
become non-nuclear states. 
  Aleksey Ivliyev, Andrey Melikhov, NTV, from the Dzerzhinskiy 
Military Academy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17991 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov083_i_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Advocates CIS Military Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Advocates CIS Military Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904064494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0538 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2904064494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Fedor Ignatov] </F>
  [Text] Alma-Ata [Almaty] 29 April TASS -- "We shall march 
together. There is no other alternative," said Kazakh Defence 
Minister Sagadat Nurmagambetov here on Friday, commenting on the 
treaty on military cooperation and some other agreements on 
military affairs, which were recently signed by the Russian and 
Kazakh presidents. 
  He made this statement, speaking before servicemen of a 
guards garrison and the Alma-Ata Higher Army School. 
  Reporting this event in its latest issue, the Kazakhstan 
SARBAZY (KAZAKH SERVICEMAN) newspaper quotes the words by the 
defence minister on the future of the armed forces of his 
republic and the Commonwealth of Independent States. 
  "There was the Soviet Union. There is the Commonwealth of 
Independent States now," he said, adding that not a single state 
of the former union can exist independently. "Therefore," the 
minister stressed, "our president has repeatedly advocated 
political consolidation and economic integration." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

