<F P=100> Turkmenistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mitterrand, Niyazov Discuss Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mitterrand, Niyazov Discuss Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804163994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1326 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2804163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondents Lyudmila </F>
Glazovskaya and Mikhail Kalmykov] 
  [Text] Ashkhabad [Ashgabat] 28 April TASS -- Continuing his 
state visit to Turkmenistan, French President Francois 
Mitterrand said today that possessing huge oil and gas deposits, 
Turkmnistan can maintain a strong position during talks with 
French industrialists. 
  The topic concerning prospects of French-Turkmen business 
cooperation in different spheres was raised during talks between 
Francois Mitterrand and Turkmen leader Saparmurad Niyazov, as 
well as at meetings of economists from both countries. 
  A large group of French industrialists, including 
representatives from such internationally established firms and 
banks as "Gas de France," "Thomson," and "Credit Commercial de 
France" are also accompanying the French head of state. They 
are not making a secret of their interest in joining large top 
priority economic projects, which are being worked out by the 
Turkmen Government, in their possibly early stage. 
  In turn, Turkmenistan, which strives to join world leaders 
on 
the international oil and gas market, sees in enhancing 
cooperation with French enterprises an opportunity to modernize 
the technical basis of this leading branch of its national 
economy, and expedite the realization of the multi-billion gas 
pipeline laying project which will supply Turkmen gas to Europe. 
  Such French industrial giants as "Elf Aquitaine," 
"Bouygues," 
and "Thomson" have already stuck firm roots in Turkmenistan. 
Besides this, great hopes are being laid on French assistance 
in the creation and development of modern infrastructure for 
transport, modern communications and banking services. 
  Judging by all accounts, these hopes have a good base. 
France, according to Francois Mitterrand, is already prepared 
to earmark over 220 million francs as credits for these 
purposes. A number of economic agreements, which, according to 
Saparmurad Niyazov, must "provide a new impulse to the 
Turkmen-French development," are planned to be signed at the end 
of the talks today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

