<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karabakh's Kocharyan Interviewed on Settlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karabakh's Kocharyan Interviewed on Settlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2504130194 Yerevan SNARK in English 0954 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2504130194 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan SNARK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [no dateline as received] "AZATAMART" weekly 
published an interview with the Chairman of the State Committee 
on defence of the Republic of Nagorno-Karabakh Robert Kocharyan. 
  In Karabakh leader's opinion, one of the obstacles hindering 
the settlement of the conflict is the existence of two parallel 
initiatives - CSCE's and Russia's - which gives the sides an 
opportunity to maneuver. Kocharyan also noted that before 
December 1993 there had been contacts with Azerbaijan on the 
highest level. However, after the beginning of the latest 
Azerbaijani offensive, the official Baku broke up those contacts. 
  During that two-month large-scale offensive the mediators, 
in 
Kocharyan's words, made no efforts to influence the attacking 
side. Instead, they patiently waited for the results of military 
actions. 
  Touching upon Turkey's and England's position, the Karabakh 
leader noted, "The attitude of those countries towards Karabakh 
was obvious since the very first days of the conflict. As to 
the oil agreements with Azerbaijan, they will only prolong 
confrontation". When asked what kind of future he sees for 
Karabakh, Kocharyan answered, "Autonomy with the widest range of 
rights within a united Armenian state". 

</TEXT>

