<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Rules Out Fresh Coup Attempt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Rules Out Fresh Coup Attempt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2904101594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0759 
GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2904101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Kolesnichenko] </F>
  [Text] New York, 29 Apr (ITAR-TASS) -- There is no danger 
of a fresh coup attempt in Russia. Russian Federation President 
Boris Yeltsin expressed confidence of this in an interview with 
the American ABC television network. There is, of course, 
opposition but it is weak, he said. It consists of nothing more 
than small groups. All state and administrative structures -- 
the army, internal troops, the Ministry of Internal Affairs -- 
are on the president's side. People have now changed. B. 
Yeltsin pointed out that he foresees no situation in which he, 
as president, could not control the situation in the country. 
  Asked whether the idea of retiring has occurred to him, the 
Russian leader said that he has thought of this, but "each time 
I found myself remembering how much I still have to do before 
June 1996." Asked about his long-term plans, B. Yeltsin merely 
said that his aides advise him to stop saying that he will not 
seek reelection. 
  During a discussion of international problems the Russian 
president was asked: "Are you not shocked, as many others 
throughout the world are, by the ethnic cleansing being carried 
out by Serbs in Bosnia?" "Not only am I shocked," B. Yeltsin 
replied, "I condemn the Serbs for not keeping their word." At 
the same time he expressed hope that a situation in which Serb 
positions would be subjected to fresh air strikes will not 
arise. "We have a partnership with the United States. Even if 
there are areas over which we disagree, we still must not react 
brusquely to them or conduct a dialogue from a position of 
strength," the Russian leader added. 
  In another part of the program he was asked about his 
health. 
"I am a healthy man," B. Yeltsin said. "This problem is being 
brought up by the opposition, especially the communists. They 
simply want to spoil my mood." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

