<H3> <TI>   Commission Preparing Report on Human Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission Preparing Report on Human Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804185794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1853 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2804185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 28 TASS -- Russia's commission on human 
rights is preparing a report on human rights in Russia which 
will be presented to President Boris Yeltsin. 
  The commission, set up by the president after the October 
1993 revolt in Moscow, will inform him about human rights abuses 
in the country, commission chairman Sergey Kovalev said on 
Thursday. 
  The commission plans to finish a national human rights 
programme by the end of May. The programme has been developed 
in cooperation with the Russian Foreign Ministry. The 
commission also handles complaints about violations of civil 
rights. 
  Kovalev, who has been appointed by the State Duma a 
commissioner on human rights, said that a draft law regulating 
the status, rights and duties of the commissioner on human 
rights is now being discussed in the Duma Committee for 
Legislation. 
  He believes that after the law has been adopted, the 
commission on human rights will have to continue working in 
order to keep the president informed about human rights in 
Russia. 

</TEXT>

