<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Reports by </F>
Diplomatic Correspondents Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and 
others] 
  [Text] The arrest of a leading member of Kazakhstan's 
Russian speaking community, Boris Suprunyuk, gave rise to 
"serious concern" in Moscow, a spokesman for Russia's Foreign 
Ministry, Grigoriy Karasin, said at Thursday's briefing. 
  According to him, his ministry has already requested 
Kazakhstan's Foreign Ministry to inform it urgently of what 
Suprunyuk is charged with, as well as of investigation and other 
actions taken against him. 
  As Karasin said, Alma Ata [Almaty] "has resorted to the 
thesis that Suprunyuk must be subjected to psychiatric 
examination." "This cannot fail to evoke memories of the 
notorious methods of combating dissent. Nevertheless we hope 
that the Kazakh authorities will display an objective and 
unbiased approach, that they will be guided by their commitments 
in the area of human rights, including those made in the 
framework of the CSCE," Karasin said. 

</TEXT>

