<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Only 16 From Every 100 Being Drafted Into Army </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Only 16 From Every 100 Being Drafted Into Army </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804194594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1818 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2804194594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Only 16 out of every 100 Russian young men aged 18 
are called up for army service. In 1988 the figure was 70. All 
the rest are relieved because of poor health or are deferred. 
Last year the Russian Army had only half of the prescribed 
strength. The spring-time call-up is also having problems. 
  These facts were reported on Thursday at a joint meeting in 
Moscow of the leaders of the medical service of the Army, the 
conscription group, the parliamentary committees for defence and 
health protection, the interior and education ministries and the 
Russian Academy of Medical Sciences. 
  Participants accounted the current miserable situation with 
conscription to the actual decline in health standards among 
young people. Last year 26.4 pct [percent] of young men were 
relieved of army service on account of poor health. Diseases of 
internal organs ranked first, mental diseases second. However, 
speakers felt that the outdated system of medical examination 
allows to call up actually sick people and simultaneously 
permits various forms of fraud. The conference formed a working 
group to draft a plan to improve health care and prepare young 
people for army service. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

