<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Advocates Cutting Top Tax Rates in 1996 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rexrodt Advocates Cutting Top Tax Rates in 1996 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3003164594 Hamburg DPA in German 1421 GMT 30 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3003164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DPA) -- In the current controversy over 
the distribution of larger tax burdens as of 1995 by means of a 
solidarity surcharge or a supplementary tax, FRG Economics 
Minister Guenter Rexrodt (Free Democratic Party of Germany) is 
already aiming at the reduction of the top tax rates as of 1996. 
In order to promote economic development, the top income and 
corporate tax rates are to be standardized and brought below 45 
percent in a three-stage tax reform. This is urgently necessary 
in international competition, the minister told DPA on Wednesday 
[30 March]. Moreover, those taxes that are independent of yield, 
such as the trade capital tax and the property tax, have to be 
reduced. The Social Democratic Party of Germany, however, 
confirmed its intention to increasingly burden "major property" 
by a land tax, a property tax, and an inheritance tax. 
  In 1993 the top income and corporate tax rates were further 
split. They are currently 45 percent for corporations, such as 
stock corporations, and 47 percent for trade or business income 
from partnerships, while the tax on private income, which also 
includes income from leasing and renting, is still 53 percent. 
According to Rexrodt, the planned tax cuts still have to be 
coordinated within the FDP and the coalition. However, "from 
the economic minister's point of view, 1996 is the date when the 
top rates have to be cut," including the taxation of private 
income. 
  However, the financial situation has to be taken into 
account. Therefore, a reform in several stages as in the 1980's 
is required. This also includes increasing the fiscal 
subsistence minimum, for which the Constitutional Court has 
called. The question of when the solidarity surcharge can be 
removed also depends on the financial situation and the economic 
development in eastern Germany, he said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

