<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Waigel Criticizes, SPD Defends Tax Reform Plans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Waigel Criticizes, SPD Defends Tax Reform Plans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3003133594 Hamburg DPA in German 1155 GMT 30 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3003133594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- The dispute between the Social Democratic 
Party of Germany [SPD] and the coalition on the SPD's government 
program, in particular its fiscal policy, continued on Wednesday 
[30 March]. Finance Minister Theo Waigel (Christian Social 
Union) criticized "a number of proposals for tax increases 
covered up as subsidy cuts." Stepping up registration of 
speculative profits would make housing construction collapse and 
cause major shifts of securities to other countries, Waigel 
pointed out. 
  These measures would not hit big capital but the employees 
depending on German capital for job-creating and securing 
measures. The finance minister also criticized that the SPD's 10 
percent supplementary tax would put a burden on corporations and 
joint-stock companies "right from the first mark." 
  Joachim Poss, the SPD Bundestag Group's monetary policy 
spokesman, defended the intention to increase taxes on "high 
assets." In the case of inheritance and property tax, tax-free 
allowances should be increased to a level where only people 
paying high amounts should face higher burdens. With 
real-estate tax, small and medium assets should not be charged 
more, either. Waigel is suggesting to taxpayers that the SPD 
wants to abolish the system of taxable values and to apply full 
values without adjusting tax-free allowances in future taxation 
of real estate and property. Although taxable values should be 
moved closer to actual current values, they must not reach the 
full amount, Poss said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

