<H3> <TI>   Martinazzoli's Resignation `Little To Do' With Loss </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Martinazzoli's Resignation `Little To Do' With Loss </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR3003140894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1258 GMT 30 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3003140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Martinazzoli Quits"] </F>
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, March 30 -- Mino Martinazzoli today 
tendered his resignation as secretary of the (ex-Christian 
Democrat) People's Party with a letter to party chairman Rosa 
Russo Jervolino. Jervolino will address a press conference at 
1800 local (1600 GMT). 
  From initial reports, it appears that the party -- the bulk 
of the once-dominant Christian Democrats -- will be led by a 
collegial body coordinated by Jervolino. 
  Earlier this year, Martinazzoli's moderate line and 
perceived 
over-cautious approach to overhauling the party was contested by 
the party's right wing, a small number of whom split to form the 
neo-conservative Democratic Christian Centre (CCD), a Berlusconi 
ally in the Freedom Front that is shortly expected to form a 
government. 
  But the relatively poor showing of the People's Party and 
the 
success claimed by the CCD in garnering 44 seats in the general 
elections was believed to have little to do with Martinazzoli's 
decision. He did not stand in the election, and had for some 
time intimated that after completing the party's transition he 
would return full-time to his lawyer's practice in the northern 
town of Brescia. 

</TEXT>

