<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Claes Reassured on Kurdish Deputies Fate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Belgium's Claes Reassured on Kurdish Deputies Fate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR3003120594 Brussels BELGA in French 1636 GMT 29 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR3003120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed LVE/MTH/PHF: "Willy Claes More Optimistic </F>
on Fate of Arrested Kurdish Deputies"; as released by Brussels 
BELGA Database] 
  [Text] Istanbul, 29 Mar (BELGA) -- Belgian Foreign Minister 
Willy Claes came out of his meeting on Tuesday [29 March] with 
Husametin Cindoruk, speaker of the Turkish Grand National 
Assembly, reassured with regard to the fate of the six Kurdish 
deputies who were arrested at the beginning of the month after 
their immunity was lifted for collusion with the Workers Party 
of Kurdistan (PKK). 
  Mr. Claes said at the end of his meeting with Cindoruk: 
"This meeting showed me the light at the end of the tunnel. I 
have every hope that major and relatively long-term progress 
will be made, and I had the feeling, after listening to Mr. 
Cindoruk's explanations, that there is less risk of very stiff 
punishments being imposed." 
  The six deputies, members of the Democratic Party [DEP], 
stand accused of "separatism" and of "endangering the integrity 
of the state," charges laying them open to the death penalty. 
  The Belgian foreign minister refused to give further details 
on the assurances he had received from Cindoruk "in the 
interests of the six deputies themselves." 
  Even though he does not know with certainty whether the 
Turk's undertakings were based on concrete facts or a on 
personal analysis, Mr. Claes expressed the hope that "the fate 
of the deputies will not be decided in the way we feared." 
  Mr. Claes had already raised the issue on Monday with his 
Turkish counterpart, Mr. Hikmet Cetin, and the head of state, 
Suleyman Demirel. He stressed at the time that sentencing the 
deputies could only lead to negative reactions from the 
international community and would adversely affect Turkey's 
credibility. 
  The foreign minister is to return to Belgium on Wednesday 
evening. 

</TEXT>

