<H3> <TI>   EC Earmarks Aid for Albania, Moldova, Bulgaria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EC Earmarks Aid for Albania, Moldova, Bulgaria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR3003143794 Antwerp DE FINANCIEEL EKONOMISCHE TIJD in Dutch 
30 Mar 94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> BR3003143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Antwerp DE FINANCIEEL EKONOMISCHE TIJD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "EU Support for Albania, Moldova, </F>
Bulgaria"] 
  [Excerpt] The European Commission (EC) has earmarked 
financial aid for Albania, Moldova, and Bulgaria. This was 
decided at a meeting of the group of 24 rich countries to 
discuss macroeconomic aid to Central and East Europe. 
  The EC proposes to make ECU35 million available to Albania. 
This EU [European Union] loan is to support the country's 
balance of payments and covers about one half of the financing 
deficit incurred during the first year of implementing the 
reform and stabilization program. 
  Over recent years, Albania has already received a loan of 
ECU70 million from the European Union. The EC is, however, 
insisting that this East European country should normalize its 
relations with commercial credit institutions so that the 
financing of private trade and direct foreign investments can 
quickly begin. 
  Moldova is to receive a long-term loan of ECU45 million from 
the EC. The Twelve agreed back in December on the principle of 
granting assistance to this former Soviet republic. The loan 
covers one third of the Moldovan financing deficit for 1994. 
  The support for the Bulgarian balance of payments is to be 
increased to ECU150 million, following the green light from the 
EU Council. An increase in support for the Romanian balance of 
payments is also likely, according to EU Commissioner Henning 
Christophersen. This European assistance comes on top of 
financial aid from the IMF and the World Bank for the economic 
reform program in Romania and Bulgaria. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

