<F P=100> IRELAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senate Approves Extradition Legislation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Senate Approves Extradition Legislation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2503130294 London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH in English 25 Mar 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM2503130294 </F>
<F P=104>  London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Richard Savill: "Dublin Closes Terrorist </F>
Extradition Loophole"] 
  [Text] Belfast -- The Irish Senate yesterday approved 
extradition legislation designed to close loopholes that have 
caused friction between London and Dublin. 
  The Extradition (Amendment) Bill, 1994, due to become law 
within two months, extends the range of offences that cannot be 
regarded as political. 
  Westminster MP's were furious when the Irish High Court 
recently freed Joseph Magee, 27, from Armagh, who was wanted in 
England in connection with the murder of Sgt Michael Newman, 34, 
in Derby on April 14, 1992. 
  Two of the three grounds given for quashing the extradition 
order were that the offence was political and that the procedure 
followed when his extradition was ordered by the lower District 
Court had been unfair. The legislation is designed to close 
both loopholes. 
  The new law would mean that people committing violent crimes 
involving firearms and explosives would no longer be able to 
claim their offence was political. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

