<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Nuclear Part' of Submarine Not Affected in Accident </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Nuclear Part' of Submarine Not Affected in Accident </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3003144094 Paris AFP in English 1422 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3003144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 30 (AFP) -- Ten sailors died in an 
accident Wednesday [30 March] aboard the French Navy 
nuclear-powered Emeraude submarine off the Mediterranean naval 
base of Toulon, military sources said. 
  They said the accident aboard the sub, armed with ballistic 
missiles, took place in a turbo engine room where electricity is 
produced with steam and in no way damaged or affected the 
nuclear part of the vessel. 
  The 10 men were in the engine room when the accident 
occurred. No further details on the cause of the disaster were 
immediately available. 
  The submarine surfaced after the accident and sailed back to 
base under its own steam. 
  Defence Minister Francois Leotard and Navy Chief of Staff 
Admiral Alain Coatanea were on their way to the base, the 
sources said. 

</TEXT>

