<H3> <TI>   Morillon Named Head of Army's Rapid Deployment Force </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Morillon Named Head of Army's Rapid Deployment Force </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3003152094 Paris AFP in English 1457 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3003152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 30 (AFP) -- General Philippe Morillon, 
who headed UN forces in Bosnia-Hercegovina in 1992-1993, was 
named head of the French Army's Rapid Deployment Force Wednesday 
[30 March]. Morillon was nominated for the position by Defence 
Minister Francois Leotard, a military spokesman said. 
  The 58-year-old Morillon will replace General Bertrand de 
Lapresle who became head of the UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) 
in ex-Yugoslavia on March 5. 
  Morillon came to public attention a year ago for his 
outspoken criticism of the shortcomings in international 
intervention in the stricken country. 
  General Morillon will begin his new job on April 5. Under 
his command will be 35,000 men, made up of four divisions and a 
logistics brigade. 

</TEXT>

