<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   * SDP Chairman Backs EU Agricultural Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    * SDP Chairman Backs EU Agricultural Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94P20562A Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 13 Mar 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20562A </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>
<F P=105>  Swedish </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Paavo Lipponen: Agriculture Cannot </F>
Get Subsidies for All Eternity"] 
  [Excerpts] That Finland got the right from the European 
Union (EU) to pay extra support to agriculture does not also 
mean that this is going to be paid for all eternity at the 
maximum level. This was stated by Social Democratic Party (SDP) 
Chairman Paavo Lipponen in Uusikaupunki and Pietasaari on 
Saturday [12 March]. 
  He was evasive as to whether the SDP should participate in 
drafting new legislation and the appropriation bills that might 
be needed. [passage omitted] 
  Lipponen repeated his proposal that the computations for 
farm 
subsidies should be determined in the same way as in the 
national wage talks, namely, by a group representing all 
interests, including the taxpayers and consumers. 
  According to Lipponen, the EU agreement's agricultural 
policies correspond in central points to goals of the SDP. The 
SDP saw that an immediate conversion to EU producer prices would 
be more advantageous than a gradual price reduction (ACA 
[expansion unknown]) that the government was seeking. 
  Lipponen asserted that the Center Party and Farmers 
Association (MTK) wanted to have a gradual reduction so that it 
would be possible to conceal the enormous price subsidies to the 
farmers and to that part of the food-processing industry owned 
by the farmers. "Now all this will be more transparent, and 
therefore the calculations regarding budget costs have shocked 
so many," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

