<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supports Greek Positions on FYROM </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Supports Greek Positions on FYROM </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3003160094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC3003160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In a statement after meeting Prime Minister Andreas 
Papandreou, Romanian President Ion Iliescu supported the Greek 
positions on The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM]. 
Iliescu noted that the Greek position on FYROM appears to be 
correct, adding that his country is not against the existence of 
FYROM. He said he hopes Greek-FYROM differences will be 
overcome through a dialogue. Iliescu added that no Balkan 
country--including Turkey of course--should participate in the 
UN peacekeeping force in the former Yugoslavia. 
  The Greek prime minister and the Romanian president 
described 
bilateral relations as warm and constructive and stressed the 
two countries' willingness to strengthen relations in the 
political, economic, and social spheres. 
  Papandreou referred to the ancient ties of friendship that 
link the two countries and added that Greece will do everything 
it can to help Romania in approaches to the European Union. 
  Iliescu and Papandreou also discussed developments in Europe 
and the problems in the Balkans. Earlier today Iliescu met 
President Konstandinos Karamanlis and discussed the latest 
developments in the former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

