<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greek Cypriots Call Report `Dangerous' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greek Cypriots Call Report `Dangerous' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3103095994 Nicosia O FILELEVTHEROS in Greek 31 Mar 94 pp 
1, 9 </F>

<F P=103> NC3103095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia O FILELEVTHEROS </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Anthos Likavyis] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Greek Cypriot side considers the increasing 
Turkish claims regarding the supposed presence and training of 
Kurdish and Armenian fighters in Cyprus as an obvious and 
outright attempt to step up pretenses. 
  An official source described these claims as unfounded and 
dangerous. Political circles note: 
  First: The Turks give details regarding the supposed 
presence of such foreigners in Cyprus to create more convincing 
impressions for third parties. 
  Second: There is an effort to involve other countries, such 
as Armenia and Azerbaijan, and cause wider concern. 
  The goal is to divert attention from impressions of the 
murder of Theofilos Yeoryiadhis [chairman of the Committee for 
Solidarity With Kurdistan] by the Turkish Secret Service and to 
justify its activities in the free areas of Cyprus with the 
usual pretenses. 
  According to Foreign Ministry officials' statements, these 
pretenses are systematically cultivated in the Turkish press and 
are reproduced in the Turkish Cypriot newspapers to convey them 
later, through propaganda bulletins, to other quarters. 
  These claims were brought back to light by [the Turkish 
Cypriot newspaper] YENI DEMOKRAT, which published the 
"information" regarding facilities offered by the Cypriot 
Government to "Kurdish and Armenian terrorists." [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

