<F P=106> [Article signed AZ: "Federal Counselor Cotti's Visit to </F>
Athens -- No Official Guarantee on the Opening of Swiss-EU 
Negotiations"] 
  [Excerpts] Athens, 30 Mar (ATS) -- Federal Counselor Flavio 
Cotti did not get any official guarantee today about the opening 
of bilateral negotiations between Switzerland and the European 
Union (EU). During his one-day visit to the Greek capital, the 
head of the Federal Department of Foreign Affairs (DFAE) 
explained to his hosts Switzerland's position regarding European 
integration. 
  At a press conference, the head of the DFAE underlined the 
"friendly" atmosphere in which the talks with his Greek 
counterpart, Karolos Papoulias, took place. Mr. Cotti also met 
with the Greek European Minister Theodoros Pangalos. Regional 
issues were also raised, namely, the situation in former 
Yugoslavia, Greek-Turkish relations, and the partition of Cyprus. 
  "Switzerland would be pleased if bilateral negotiations with 
the EU began during the Greek presidency," which will come to an 
end in June, according to Mr. Cotti. The head of the DFAE 
stated that, if those negotiations began "quickly enough," this 
would "create excellent psychological conditions in 
Switzerland." The long-term "strategic goal" of Switzerland is 
indeed a "full and complete" membership in the European Union, 
the federal counselor added. 
<H5>  No Official Guarantee </H5>
  Questioned by ATS, Greek Minister Theodoros Pangalos 
remained 
reserved about the opening of bilateral negotiations between 
Switzerland and the EU during Greece's EU Presidency. 
Nevertheless, Mr. Pangalos said it was likely that those 
negotiations would begin before the end of the year. [passage 
omitted] 
  Mr. Papoulias for his part said that Mr. Cotti's visit, the 
first by the head of the Swiss diplomatic corps since 1976, 
testified to the "political will" of both countries to develop 
and strengthen bilateral relations. He "thanked" Switzerland 
for its contribution to the financing of the UN peacekeeping 
forces in Cyprus. 

</TEXT>

