<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Finland Becomes 14th Member of </F>
European Space Agency"; as released by EUROPEAN REPORT] 
  [Text] Finland has just joined the ranks of the European 
Space Agency (ESA). The Secretary-General of Finland's Ministry 
for Trade and Industry Matti Vuoria, and ESA Director-General 
Jean Marie Lutton signed an Agreement which admits Finland as 
the 14th member of the Agency. Finland will officially receive 
the official status of full participating member on January 1, 
1995, once its Parliament has ratified the Agreement, and will 
then join its two Scandinavian neighbours, Norway and Sweden, 
which are already ESA members. Since 1987, Finland had held the 
status of associate member, and is already involved in a number 
of ESA programmes. The new member intends to become more 
involved in space science programmes, as well as earth 
observation and satellite telecommunications. ESA member 
countries are: Austria, Belgium, Denmark, France, Germany, 
Ireland, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland 
and the UK. 

</TEXT>

